        <body><div type="bibliography">
                     
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#gasperini1967a"/>, p. 166, n. <citedRange>7</citedRange> (ph.) 
                    (= <bibl><ptr target="#gasperini2008"/>, p. <citedRange>78</citedRange> (ph.)</bibl>)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>000440</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><orig>κετον</orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
                <p>Intraduisible.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
                <p>Intraducibile.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>غير قابل للترجمه بشكل جيد</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>This might be part of a personal name <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ἄλκετος</foreign> (at the accusative case) or 
                    even <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ἀλκέτων</foreign>, hitherto unattested, but well formed.</p>
                <p>Addendum 2022: Alternatively, we might also read <foreign xml:lang="grc">[ὁ δεῖνα ἀνέθη]κε τὸν [- - </foreign>. To choose between both eventualities seems impoosible.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
